# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 uses a simple `[INST]`/`[/INST]` chat format that differs from the newer Ministral 3 format (which uses `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[TOOL_CALLS]`, etc.). This change adds a dedicated handler for the older v0.3 instruct format so it can be detected and rendered correctly without relying on the Jinja autoparser.

**Only file modified:** `common/chat.cpp`

---

## Step 1: Add the handler function (after line 1517)

Insert `common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3` between the end of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` (line 1517) and `namespace workaround` (line 1519).

This is a simple handler — no PEG parser, no grammar, no tool support. It manually builds the prompt string:

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    std::string system_message;
    size_t start_idx = 0;
    if (!inputs.messages.empty() &&
        inputs.messages[0].value("role", "") == "system") {
        system_message = inputs.messages[0].value("content", "");
        start_idx = 1;
    }

    std::string prompt = tmpl.bos_token();
    bool first_user = true;

    for (size_t i = start_idx; i < inputs.messages.size(); ++i) {
        const auto & msg = inputs.messages[i];
        auto role    = msg.value("role", "");
        auto content = msg.value("content", "");

        if (role == "user") {
            if (first_user && !system_message.empty()) {
                prompt += "[INST] " + system_message + "\n" + content + " [/INST]";
            } else {
                prompt += "[INST] " + content + " [/INST]";
            }
            first_user = false;
        } else if (role == "assistant") {
            prompt += content + tmpl.eos_token();
        }
    }

    data.prompt = prompt;
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;

    return data;
}
```

Key decisions:
- Uses `tmpl.bos_token()` / `tmpl.eos_token()` (not hardcoded `<s>`/`</s>`) — follows existing patterns
- System message extracted from first message and prepended to first user turn
- Assistant content followed by EOS token
- Other roles (tool, etc.) silently ignored — this is a content-only handler

---

## Step 2: Add detection logic in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` (after line 1644)

Insert between the Ministral 3 check (ends line 1644) and the GPT-OSS check (starts line 1646). This ordering is critical: Ministral 3 templates also contain `[INST]`/`[/INST]`, but they are caught first by their `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` check.

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v3 - simple [INST]/[/INST] format without [SYSTEM_PROMPT] tags
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos && src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

---

## Verification

1. **Build**: `cmake --build build` — confirm no compilation errors
2. **Format check**: The multi-turn output should match:
   - With system: `<s>[INST] {system}\n{user1} [/INST]{assistant1}</s>[INST] {user2} [/INST]`
   - Without system: `<s>[INST] {user1} [/INST]{assistant1}</s>[INST] {user2} [/INST]`
3. **Existing tests**: Run `ctest` to confirm no regressions — all existing handlers and detection logic are untouched

